Biden hammered Sanders over his record on guns and voting five times against the Brady Bill.

Sanders did vote against multiple iterations of the Brady Bill, five times in total, according to PolitiFact. However, Sanders was right about his D- rating from the NRA. (9/9)

Klobuchar and Joe Biden got into it over who wrote which gun control bill.

Biden wrote the Violence Against Women Act, which only covers certain relationships. Klobuchar wrote a bill that closes that loophole. (8/9)

Bloomberg said that he released his tax returns as NYC mayor.

That's not exactly true. During his 3 terms as NYC mayor, he made highly redacted, vague versions of his tax documents available to reporters for a couple hours each year. Not the full and complete returns. (7/9)

Bloomberg and Klobuchar went after President Trump for neglecting the institutions that could help the U.S. face the coronavirus threat.

The White House does not have a top pandemic official and while the president has sought cuts to the CDC, he has not defunded it. (6/9)

Sen. Sanders claimed that according to studies, 'Medicare for All' will save money. 

Many studies do say that his Medicare for All proposal would save money, but other studies say it would cost more than the current system, measured as a share of GDP. (5/9)

Sen. Klobuchar said Wisconsin and Georgia kicked hundreds of thousands of people off their voting rolls.

Georgia did purge 100,000 inactive voters but Wisconsin hasn't completed its purge yet. It's important to note that purges are a normal part of roll maintenance. (4/9)

Sen. Sanders says half of America lives paycheck to paycheck and real wage increases were under 1%.

Real average hourly earnings increased 0.6% for the year ending in 2019 and studies have found that around half of all Americans live paycheck to paycheck. (3/9)

Mike Bloomberg claims that he reined in the use of stop-and-frisk after it got "out of control," but this is a false representation of events.

The practice was scaled back due to a 2013 court order declaring the policy unconstitutional, not Bloomberg's change of heart. (2/9)

How concerned should I be?

Concerned enough to pay attention. Stay on top of CDC updates and guidance, as well as from state and local health departments. Take the time to plan for what you'll do if local transmission of the virus occurs in your city. https://t.co/rfoGwIaTXV

Should I wear a face mask?

Not unless you are the one who is sick.

The CDC doesn‚Äôt currently recommend any healthy person wear a mask, and doctors warn fiddling with putting on and taking off a mask could backfire by exposing your hands to your face. https://t.co/rfoGwIaTXV

How does COVID-19 compare to the flu?

COVID-19 appears to be more fatal than the flu, with a fatality rate believed to be around 2%, while the flu's fatality rate is less than 1%.

Compared to past coronaviruses, such as SARS and MERS, however, most COVID-19 cases are mild.

While it's possible the virus could be transmitted by touching objects or surfaces contaminated with COVID-19, health experts don't currently believe that's primarily how it's transmitted. https://t.co/rfoGwIaTXV

How is it transmitted?

Person-to-person transmission is mostly likely between people in close contact. When an infected person sneezes or coughs, respiratory droplets could land on people nearby or could possibly be inhaled by those people. https://t.co/rfoGwIaTXV
Since the symptoms are similar to those of pneumonia, influenza and the common cold, only a diagnostic test can confirm whether an individual has coronavirus. https://t.co/rfoGwIaTXV

What are the symptoms?

Novel coronavirus can cause symptoms ranging from mild to severe, including cough, fever and shortness of breath. https://t.co/rfoGwIaTXV
